value.0: Ellaefar is one of Winya's best. She is a proud moon elven warrior, sworn to protect the city and its inhabitants with her life. She personally requested the assignment of guarding Winya's leading Council, and watches over each meeting with sharp eyes.

This shield is commonly mass produced during times of war to protect valuable field officers. Sometimes they gather in merchants inventories during periods of peace or when a surplus has been made. They are definitely more practical than elaborate, a fairly straight-forward protection.
A protector of Winya Ravana, these elves were called from Evermeet itself.

Shethal is a cleric and wizard of Labelas Enoreth. Often seen at the side or on the shoulder of the sun elf is her snow white owl familiar. She has grisly scarring on her face and left arm from exposure to immense amounts of positive energy during the siege of Kohlingen.

Dogma of Corellon Larethian: The elves are sculptors and wardens of magic's endless mysteries. Bring forth the beauty that envelops and lets the spirit gambol unfettered. Seek out new experiences and new ways. Ward against those that would destroy what they cannot create. Commune with the natural and mystical world. Be ever vigilant against the return of the banished darkness and be strong in heart against the corruption of the Spider Queen.

This altar is made of shiny marble and silver. The crescent moon of Corellon Larethian floats on the wall above it, and there is a white cloth on the altar. The most sacred of prayers and sacrifices to the Father of the Elves are done here.

If you stare into the clear orb for long enough, you can see something in there: A green island in the middle of an ocean, slender towers glimmering in the sunlight and elven figures walking on its shores.

This crystal is a way to contact Evermeet from Winya. It's rarely used, but the possibility is there for times of extreme distress. Then again, it's ancient magic and Vilmandel is the only one on Amia who knows how to operate it.
The little sack is made of fine-spun silk, tightly stitched. Visitors often offer a few coins as a donation to Winya Ravana and the church of Corellon Larethian.

This large book must contain thousands of pages, but not half of it is used yet. Elvolia, Winya's faithful and hard-working clerk, scribes down information about each citizen into the book. Records of every legal citizen who ever lived in Winya can be found within its pages.

This masterful sculpture of dolphins is dedicated to Deep Sashelas, the patron of aquatic elves. The Knowledgeable One also represents beauty, creation, knowledge and magic to the elves. Even if not greatly worshipped by elves on land, this shrine is a constant reminder of the Seldarine's, and therefore the Tel'Quessir's, unity.

This is a spell focus of sorts, a crystal used to empower divinations. It does little on its own, but most wizards and priests find it helps them to concentrate and amplify the effects of their divining spells.
Some ash and gold chips have been left behind on the trays, likely measured out as ingredients for some potion or other. It seems the mages should learn some tidiness.

Something glows and moves inside of this glass tube, but you find it hard to say what exactly it is. It has no form or colour, yet it takes any shape you can imagine and shines in colours you didn't even know about. It's almost organic, but it's certainly not an organism. One might make a wild guess and say it's magic, but those educated in the Art would probably give a long and dry lecture about such nonsense, and explain just what kind of a manifestation of the Weave this energy really is.

This huge tome is bound in hardened leather. Elven runes cover its surface, some of them bearing minor enchantments.

Within, the clean white pages are filled with colourful and wonderous pictures and flowing handwriting. The book describes the nature and function of High Magic, known spells cast in recent millenia, and introduces notable High Mages of the past. There's even an entire chapter dedicated to Mythal spells.

To outsiders, this mirror seems a little out-of-place in such a spiritual place. In truth, some elves enjoy meditating infront of it, "trying to see below the surface." It's Evereskan handicraft, a rare masterpiece.

Dogma of Sehanine Moonbow:  Life is series of mysteries whose secrets are veiled by the Luminous Cloud. As the spirit transcends its mortal bounds and new mysteries are uncovered, a higher form is achieved and the cycle of life continues. Through contemplation and meditation, communion with the Lady of Dreams is achieved. Through dreams, visions, and omens revealed in sleep or the reverie, the Daughter of the Night Sky unveils the next step along the path and the next destination on the endless journey of mystic wonder that is life and death and life.

This book is bound in light wood covers. The symbol of Angharradh, three interconnecting rings on a downward pointing triangle, is printed on the front cover. The book contains hymns and prayers to the Triune Goddess, celebrating the unity of the Tel'Quessir. Many of the texts are religious songs but some resemble philosophical and theological poems pondering the paradox of difference between elves being the key to unity.

Dogma of Deep Sashelas:  Swim the great currents and the shallow seas. Exult in the everchanging beauty and life of the bounteous Undersea. Revel in the joy of creation and increase its myriad aspects. Seek not to hold that which is everchanging, but instead love the change itself. Seek out fellow swimmers who honor the ways of the Lord of the Undersea, and ally with them against those who see only the darkness of the deeps. Follow the way of the dolphin. Promote the use of the seas by all reasonable folk for all time to come; fight those who would hoard its riches or pollute its depths.
